\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 Hook Trade-offs\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0
\fs24 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Git Hooks
\f0\b0 : Native to version control; run even if an agent runs in fully autonomous, non-interactive mode. However, they can be bypassed using the 
\f3\fs26 --no-verify
\f0\fs24  flag during a commit.\
\ls3\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Agent Hooks
\f0\b0 : Capture events mid-trajectory to block dangerous tool commands, but they do not protect the repository if a developer bypasses the IDE.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \strokec2 Local gates reinforce good developer habits and help catch vulnerabilities instantly. Remember, however, that local gates can be bypassed, meaning your remote, isolated CI/CD pipeline remains your ultimate, unbypassable security barrier.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0
